{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17611764","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17611764"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:15:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:15:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16241"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16241","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16241"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.28,0.39,0.14,0.08,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8932"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80856"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8932","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8932"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16241"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66179"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"377"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"10734"},{"type":"tags","id":"10773"},{"type":"tags","id":"10776"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21256"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27644"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80856","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80856"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EBreast cancer is a common malignancy that can occur sporadically or as part of inherited cancer syndromes. Understanding the proportion of hereditary cases is important for genetic counselling and risk assessment.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the percentage of breast cancers that are hereditary?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Less than 10%","10-25%","26-50%","51-75%","Greater than 75%"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EOnly \u003Cstrong\u003Eless than 10%\u003C/strong\u003E of all breast cancers are truly hereditary, with BRCA1 and BRCA2 mutations being the most commonly identified genetic causes. This relatively small percentage highlights that most breast cancers are sporadic rather than inherited.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe remaining options represent common misconceptions:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E10-25%\u003C/strong\u003E overestimates the hereditary component\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E26-50%\u003C/strong\u003E significantly overestimates the hereditary component\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E51-75%\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Egreater than 75%\u003C/strong\u003E are far too high and would incorrectly suggest that most breast cancers are inherited\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile family history is an important risk factor, the vast majority (90-95%) of breast cancers occur sporadically. This understanding is crucial for appropriate genetic testing and counselling strategies.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Only 5-10% of breast cancers are due to inherited genetic mutations, with BRCA1 and BRCA2 being the most common.","The majority of breast cancers (90-95%) are sporadic or non-hereditary in nature."],"references":["Apostolou P, Fostira F. Hereditary breast cancer: the era of new susceptibility genes. Biomed Res Int. 2013;2013:747318. doi: 10.1155/2013/747318. Epub 2013 Mar 21. PMID: 23586058; PMCID: PMC3618918.","Easton DF. Familial risks of breast cancer. Breast Cancer Res. 2002;4(5):179-81. doi: 10.1186/bcr448. Epub 2002 Aug 2. PMID: 12223120; PMCID: PMC138740.","Shen L, Zhang S, Wang K, Wang X. Familial Breast Cancer: Disease Related Gene Mutations and Screening Strategies for Chinese Population. Front Oncol. 2021 Dec 1;11:740227. doi: 10.3389/fonc.2021.740227. PMID: 34926254; PMCID: PMC8671637.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66179"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16241"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66179","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66179"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-23T10:23:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-23T10:23:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8932"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80856"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{